A central requirement and probably one of the biggest challenges is the development of a laser system suitable for driving the nuclear transition in the clock concept. Ideally, the laser light should be extremely stable, cw and ultra-narrow-band with a bandwidth very well in the mHz-range [185, 215]. Unfortunately no such laser at about 150 nm wavelength is available today. This may, however, be subject to change in the future. The non-linear crystal currently used for second-harmonic generation (and therefore also for the generation of cw laser light at the shortest wavelength) is KBe2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
