In the internal conversion (IC) process the nucleus transfers its excitation energy to the electronic shell, leading to the emission of an electron as shown in Fig. 34b. The IC process was experimentally described by Meitner in 1924 [117, 217] and the theory was developed in the following decades (see [377] and references therein). A detailed theoretical discussion can be found in [296, 297]. The IC decay rate is usually expressed in terms of the IC coefficient, defined as the ratio between the IC- and the direct radiative-decay rate18αic=ΓicΓγ.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
