There is no consistent definition of nuclear excitation by electron transition (NEET) in the literature. Historically, NEET was proposed in 1973 by Morita [231] as a process in which an electron from a bound excited state decays, thereby exciting the nucleus. It can therefore be considered as the reverse of BIC. It was assumed that an electron is removed from a deep shell level by, e.g., synchrotron radiation and subsequently an electron from a higher lying shell state fills the vacancy. The energy that is set free in this process can couple to the nucleus if a nuclear level matches the resonance condition. Experimentally the process was studied for 189\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$^{189}$$\end{document}Os [250], 237\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$^{237}$$\end{document}Np [307], 197\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$^{197}$$\end{document}Au [98] (see also [190]) and 193\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
